# Performance Optimization Best Practices (meApp iOS)

## 1. Memory Management
- Avoid retain cycles in closures.
- Use weak references when appropriate.
- Dispose of resources properly.
- Monitor memory usage.

## 2. State Management & View Updates
- Use `@State` for simple local state, `@Binding` for parent-child communication, and `@StateObject` for reference types owned by a view.
- Prefer `@StateObject` over `@ObservedObject` when instantiating objects within a view to avoid reinitialization.
- Use `@EnvironmentObject` for shared app-wide data, but avoid for deeply nested dependencies.
- Minimize view body computation: extract reusable subviews and avoid redundant calculations in the `body`.

## 3. List & ScrollView Performance
- Use `LazyVStack`/`LazyHStack` instead of `VStack`/`HStack` for long or dynamic lists.
- Always provide a stable `id` for items in `ForEach`.
- Avoid using `.onAppear` for every list item as it can cause performance bottlenecks.

## 4. View Hierarchy & Layout
- Avoid deep view nesting; flatten hierarchies and extract reusable components.
- Use `Group` to avoid unnecessary wrapper views.
- Use `GeometryReader` sparingly, as it recalculates on every layout change and can impact performance if overused, especially in lists.

## 5. Animations & Transitions
- Use implicit animations only when necessary.
- Prefer `withAnimation` for smooth UI transitions.
- Use `.animation(nil)` for views that should not animate during state updates.
- Avoid excessive or complex animations, especially in frequently updated views.

## 6. Image Optimization
- Use `.resizable()` and `.aspectRatio(contentMode:)` to control image scaling.
- Use `Image(uiImage:)` for optimized UIKit integration when needed.
- Cache remote images using `AsyncImage` or a custom cache.

## 7. Network Optimization
- Use efficient API calls and proper caching.
- Handle offline scenarios gracefully.
- Optimize image and data loading for minimal blocking of the main thread.

## 8. Profiling & Tools
- Always profile your app using Xcode Instruments (e.g., Time Profiler, Memory Graph, SwiftUI View Body) to measure actual performance gains.
- Use the SwiftUI Previews performance diagnostics to catch slow view updates early.

## 9. Example: Optimized List
```swift
struct ListView: View {
    let items = Array(1...1000)
    var body: some View {
        ScrollView {
            LazyVStack {
                ForEach(items, id: \ .self) { item in
                    Text("Item \(item)")
                        .padding()
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## 10. Example: StateObject vs ObservedObject
```swift
class UserSettings: ObservableObject {
    @Published var username = "Kirit"
}

struct ContentView: View {
    @StateObject var settings = UserSettings()
    var body: some View {
        NavigationView {
            HomeView().environmentObject(settings)
        }
    }
}
```

